article.headline: Minnesota 83, Lipscomb 66
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- With five new starters, Minnesota expected growing pains this season. But the Gophers didn't expect to lean on their two newest faces to bail them out of their first jam. Vincent Grier scored 23 points and Dan Coleman added 21 as the Gophers opened their season with an 83-66 victory over Lipscomb on Sunday. Minnesota (1-0) struggled early, falling behind by as much as seven points in the first half against Lipscomb, a Nashville, Tenn., school playing just its second season of NCAA Division I basketball. But in the second half, the Gophers' defense clamped down and the offense took advantage of 14 steals and 23 Lipscomb turnovers to pull away. "I thought in the second half we played great with our intensity," said Grier, a junior college transfer who hit 9-of-10 shots from the field and added five rebounds and four assists. "We opened it up with our defense and got a couple of steals. We just had those first-game jitters but we had to stay poised and just play our game." Coleman, a redshirt freshman who transferred last year from Boston College, made his Williams Arena debut a memorable one by hitting 3-of-4 3-pointers. After making just 1-of-5 shots in the first half, Coleman hit six of 10 after the break. "I think I just relaxed and let the game come to me," Coleman said. "I think it was just a group calming. Like Vince said, 'first-game jitters." Sophomore guard Brian Fisk paced Lipscomb (0-1) with 23 points and six rebounds, while Cameron Robinson scored 12 and James Poindexter added 11. The Bisons showed early they wouldn't be intimidated by their first Big Ten opponent, taking a 24-17 lead on a 3-pointer by Fisk midway through the first half. The Gophers scored the next eight points, taking their first lead at 25-24 on Aaron Robinson's 3-pointer with 8:20 remaining in the first half, but another 3-pointer by Fisk helped the Bisons answer and stretch their lead back to five. However, Minnesota used an 11-2 run over the final 2:40 of the first half to take a 36-32 lead at the break. Junior J'son Stamper hit a pair of baskets in the run and freshman Spencer Tollackson connected on a short jump shot with seven seconds left to give the Gophers their biggest lead of the first half. "This is a learning experience," Fisk said. "They're a Big Ten team, and we still feel we have a chance to play with anyone." Freshman Rico Tucker hit 9-of-10 free throws and finished with 11 points and four steals for Minnesota, while center Jeff Hagen scored 10 points and blocked a career-high seven shots. But Hagen, Minnesota's most experienced player, also committed six turnovers and said the Gophers would learn a lesson from the close call. "We can't just come out like we did and expect the name on our chest to win us games," Hagen said. "We have to take better care of the ball -- we can't have our big guy with six turnovers. That's definitely a bad, bad stat. "They hit some tough shots and you have to give them credit," Hagen added. "But we knew if we came out with our style of ball, we'd be OK. We still have a long way to go but we're working on it." And coming off a 12-18 season with so many new faces on the roster, Minnesota coach Dan Monson said they're taking nothing for granted. "I think this is a team, whether it's Lipscomb or whoever, where we need to be pleased with a win," he said. "That's the ultimate goal. This is a starting point, and we're happy to start with a win."
